<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class=m>Zeno of Elea’s arguments against a motion are reviewed in this
paper. The paradoxes of Dichotomy, Achilles, Stadium and Arrow are serially
discussed. A principal difference between potentially infinite and actually
infinite is revealed. It is shown that so-called “solutions” of Zeno’s
arguments are untenable. In addition, this paper contains inference that the
problem of the description of a motion exists until now. That is why the way
out of Zeno’s paradoxes requires revising many of our concepts to escape the
contradictions discovered by Eleatic philosopher’s fruitful arguments.</p>

